# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xbox-one
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xbox-one/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:xbox-one/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:xbox-one/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:xbox-one/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] 1080p video signals are supported by ATSC standards in the United States and DVB standards in Europe.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Applications of the 1080p standard include television broadcasts, Blu-ray Discs, smartphones, Internet content such as YouTube videos and Netflix TV shows and movies, consumer-grade televisions and projectors, computer monitors and video game consoles.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Small camcorders, smartphones and digital cameras can capture still and moving images in 1080p resolution.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Any display device that advertises 1080p typically refers to the ability to accept a 1080p signal and display it with a native resolution of at least 1080 lines vertically (as well as the ability to upscale lower-resolution material to 1080p).
[src:xbox-one/1080p] This means that the display is not over-scanning, under-scanning, or reinterpreting the signal to a lower resolution.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] The HD ready 1080p logo program, by DigitalEurope, requires that certified TV sets support 1080p 24 fps, 1080p 25 fps, 1080p 50 fps, and 1080p 60 fps formats, among other requirements, with fps meaning frames per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] For live broadcast applications, a high-definition progressive scan format operating at 1080p at 50 or 60 frames per second was being evaluated as a future standard for moving picture acquisition, although 24 fps was used for shooting movies.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Most current revisions of SMPTE 372M, SMPTE 424M and EBU Tech 3299 require YCbCr color space and 4:2:2 chroma subsampling for transmitting 1080p50 (nominally 2.08 Gbit/s) and 1080p60 signal.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] In the United States, the original ATSC standards for HDTV supported 1080p video, but only at the frame rates of 23.976, 24, 25, 29.97 and 30 frames per second (colloquially known as **1080p24**, **1080p25** and **1080p30**).
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Such frame rates require H.264/AVC *High Profile Level 4.2*, while standard HDTV frame rates only require Level 4.0.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] This update is not expected to result in widespread availability of 1080p60 programming, since most of the existing digital receivers in use would only be able to decode the older, less-efficient MPEG-2 codec, and because there is a limited amount of bandwidth for subchannels.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] In Europe, 1080p25 signals have been supported by the DVB suite of broadcasting standards.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] The 1080p50 format is considered to be a future-proof production format and, eventually, a future broadcasting format.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] 1080p50 broadcasting should require the same bandwidth as 1080i50 signal and only 15–20% more than that of 720p50 signal due to increased compression efficiency, though 1080p50 production requires more bandwidth or more efficient codecs such as JPEG 2000, high-bitrate MPEG-2, or H.264/AVC and HEVC.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] EBU requires that legacy MPEG-4 AVC decoders should avoid crashing in the presence of SVC or 1080p50 (and higher resolution) packets.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] The ITU-T BT.2100 standard that includes Advanced 1080p video was subsequently published in July 2016.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] In practice, 1080p typically refers to a 1920 × 1080p raster with a 16:9 picture aspect ratio.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] The following is a list of other resolutions with a picture height of 1080 lines that are sometimes referred as 1080p.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] In the United States, 1080p over-the-air broadcasts are currently available in select stations in some cities in the US via ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations where as ATSC 3.0 is currently rolling out throughout the U.S.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] The majority of the stations that broadcast at 1080p are CBS and NBC stations and affiliates.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] All other stations do not broadcast at 1080p and usually broadcast at 720p60 (including when simulcasting in ATSC 3.0) or 1080i60 (outside of ATSC 3.0) encoded with MPEG-2.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] There is also technical restrictions with ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations that prevent stations from airing at 1080p.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] While converting to ATSC 3.0 is voluntary by TV Stations, there is no word when any of the major networks will consider airing at 1080p in the foreseeable future on a national scale, although they are required to broadcast ATSC signals for at least five years thereafter.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] However, satellite services (e.g., DirecTV, XstreamHD and Dish Network) use the 1080p/24-30 format with MPEG-4 AVC/H.264 encoding for pay-per-view movies that are downloaded in advance via satellite or on-demand via broadband.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] For material that originates from a progressive scanned 24 frame/s source (such as film), MPEG-2 lets the video be coded as 1080p24, irrespective of the final output format.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] These progressively-coded frames are tagged with metadata (literally, fields of the PICTURE header) instructing a decoder how to perform a 3:2 pulldown to interlace them.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] While the formal output of the MPEG-2 decoding process from such stations is 1080i60, the actual content is coded as 1080p24 and can be viewed as such (using a process known as inverse telecine) since no information is lost even when the broadcaster performs the 3:2 pulldown.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] In June 2016, German television stations began broadcasting 1080p50 high-definition video on eight channels via the HEVC-encoded DVB-T2 protocol.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] A total of 40 channels were available on March 29, 2017 (Phase 1).
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Blu-ray Discs are able to hold 1080p HD content, and most movies released on Blu-ray Disc produce a full 1080p HD picture when the player is connected to a 1080p HDTV via an HDMI cable.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Generally this type of video runs at 30 to 40 megabits per second, compared to the 3.5 megabits per second for conventional standard definition broadcasts.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Smartphones with 1080p Full HD display have been available on the market since 2012.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] As of 2014, it is the standard for mid-range to high-end smartphones, with many flagship devices using even higher resolutions, such as Quad HD (1440p) or Ultra HD (2160p).
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Several websites, including YouTube, allow videos to be uploaded in the 1080p format.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] YouTube streams 1080p content at approximately 4 megabits per second compared to Blu-ray's 30 to 40 megabits per second.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Digital distribution services like Hulu and HBO Max also deliver 1080p content, such as movies available on Blu-ray Disc or from broadcast sources.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] This can include distribution services like peer-to-peer websites and public or private tracking networks.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Netflix has been offering high quality 1080p content in the US and other countries through select internet providers since 2013.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] As of 2012, most consumer televisions being sold provide 1080p inputs, mainly via HDMI, and support full high-definition resolutions.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] 1080p resolution is available in all types of television, including plasma, LCD, DLP front and rear projection and LCD projection.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] For displaying film-based 1080i60 signals, a scheme called 3:2 pulldown reversal (reverse telecine) is beginning to appear in some newer 1080p displays, which can produce a true 1080p quality image from film-based 1080i60 programs.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Similarly, 25fps content broadcast at 1080i50 may be deinterlaced to 1080p content with no loss of quality or resolution.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] AV equipment manufacturers have adopted the term *Full HD* to mean a set can display all available HD resolutions up to 1080p.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] The term is misleading, however, because it does not guarantee the set is capable of rendering digital video at all frame rates encoded in source files with 1920 X 1080 pixel resolution.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Most notably, a "Full HD" set is not guaranteed to support the 1080p24 format, leading to consumer confusion.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] DigitalEurope (formerly EICTA) maintains the HD ready 1080p logo program that requires the certified TV sets to support 1080p24, 1080p50, and 1080p60, without overscan/underscan and picture distortion.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Most widescreen cathode-ray tube (CRT) and liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors can natively display 1080p content.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] For example, widescreen WUXGA monitors support 1920 × 1200 resolution, which can display a pixel for pixel reproduction of the 1080p (1920 × 1080) format.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Additionally, many 23, 24, and 27-inch (690 mm) widescreen LCD monitors use 1920 × 1200 as their native resolution; 30 inch displays can display beyond 1080p at up to 2560 × 1600 (1600p).
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Many 27" monitors have native resolutions of 2560 × 1440 and hence operate at 1440p.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Sony has their first and formerly Vaio 1080p laptop, VPCCB17FG, in 2011, and since Asus also has their first 4K laptop GL502 which was formerly branded Republic of Gamers in 2017, 1080p has also become the nowadays lowest standard for laptops.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] While Microsoft's original Xbox, launched as part of the sixth generation of video game consoles in 2001, could support a 1080i output in limited circumstances, support for 1080p began with the launch of the seventh generation of home video game consoles in 2005.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Both the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 were capable of outputting at 1080p, with only the Wii unable to support the resolution.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] All home video game consoles launched as part of the eighth generation, which began in 2012 with the launch of the Wii U, were capable of 1080p outputs.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Mid-generation hardware revisions and new models introduced by Sony and Microsoft to their respective PlayStation 4 and Xbox One consoles added the capability of outputting at 4K UHD — well beyond 1080p.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Moreover, this mid-generational improvement in computing power also represented a leap in the ability of video game consoles to render gaming content at a 1080p resolution or higher, rather than relying on upscaling.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] This trend continued with the launch of the current ninth generation of video game consoles in 2020, in which both Sony's PlayStation 5 and Microsoft's Xbox Series X were advertised as including 8K UHD support.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] As of 2024, however, neither console yet supports outputting the standard and PlayStation 5 packaging no longer advertises the feature.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] The Nintendo Switch console displays in resolutions up to 1080p when docked, while the successor console, Nintendo Switch 2, displays in 1080p when undocked, and up to 4K when docked.
[src:xbox-one/1080p] Many cameras—professional and consumer still, action and video cameras, including DSLR cameras—and other devices with built-in cameras such as laptops, smartphones and tablet computers, can capture 1080p24, 1080p25, 1080p30 or 1080p60 video, often encoding it in progressive segmented frame format.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] The **1292 Advanced Programmable Video System** is a second-generation home video game console released by Hong Kong company Radofin in 1979.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] It is part of a group of software-compatible consoles which include the Interton VC 4000 and the Voltmace Database.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] The 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System included its power pack inside the console instead of an exterior power pack.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] An expensive £49 (equivalent to £288.01 in 2025 pounds) Hobby Module was available which gave 6.5 kilobits of user-programmable memory and had a 5-pin DIN socket to allow software to be saved to a cassette tape player.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] This converted the unit into halfway between a home computer and an ordinary gaming console.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] The user had to be familiar with programming in Signetics 2650 assembly language and the unconventional ways and register architecture of the Signetics 2650 processor.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] The console was produced by different companies and sold with different names.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] Although all variants have identical computational hardware, changes to the dimensions of the cartridge slot on some variants result in cartridges not always being interchangeable between systems.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] The following is a table of the console variants grouped by cartridge compatibility.
[src:xbox-one/1292-advanced-programmable-video-system] Although, not much information is known about the release dates of the cartridges, the total number of the games should be 59 (33 games released by Radofin between 1977 and 1978, 19 games for the Interton VC 4000 and compatibles after 1978, and 7 more games released around 1980).
[src:xbox-one/1440p] 1440p video mastered from 4:3 ratio content can be displayed with 1920×1440 or higher resolution such as QXGA or 2304×1440 with scaling, windowboxing, or pillarboxing.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] Widescreen 16:9 aspect ratio 1440p requires 2560×1440 (WQHD) resolution, possible with WQXGA, 2560×1920, or higher resolution with letterboxing, scaling, or windowboxing.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] The HDMI 1.3 specification supports WQXGA, and hence widescreen 1440p.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] Early 1440p computer displays became commonly available in 2010.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] Dell's UltraSharp U2711 monitor was released in 2010 as WQHD, with a 1440p widescreen.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] The 27-inch Apple LED Cinema Display released in 2010 also had a native resolution of 2560 × 1440, as did the Apple Thunderbolt Display which was sold from July 2011 to June 2016.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] MacBook with Retina Display (2012) is also one of the earliest laptops that utilise 1440p widescreen.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] By 2020, 1440p had expanded to a common resolution for computer gaming, with multiple video cards available that supported high frame rates at that resolution.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] In early 2021, QHD gaming laptops with fast refresh rates were introduced by multiple computer manufacturers.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] According to Steam's July 2024 Hardware & Software Survey, the resolution 2560 x 1440 has increased in overall usage on Steam by ~0.7% from May 2024, totaling to ~20% of its total userbase.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] In relation to smartphones, 1440p displays are sometimes marketed as "Quad HD", as it is four times the resolution of 720p high definition.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] The Vivo Xplay 3S, released December 2013, was the first smartphone to use a 1440p display; by 2015, 1440p had seen wider adoption by high-end flagship smartphones from major companies.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] An example of a smartphone with a 1440p display is the 1st generation Google Pixel XL.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] In September 2020, Microsoft revealed the Xbox Series S would support a resolution of 1440p at 120 FPS.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] In July 2022, Sony added 1440p support for the PlayStation 5.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] In April 2025, Nintendo revealed the Nintendo Switch 2 would support a resolution of 1440p at 120 FPS output via HDMI when playing in TV mode.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] The label "2K" is sometimes used to refer to 2560 × 1440 (commonly known as 1440p).
[src:xbox-one/1440p] This is inconsistent with "4K" denoting approximately 4,000 horizontal pixels, which makes 1920 or 2048 pixels wide the closest to "2K", a label which predates the use of 2560 × 1440.
[src:xbox-one/1440p] Some sources and manufacturers prefer "2.5K" as a term for 2560 × 1440 to avoid this confusion, and there is a similar "2.7K" (2720 × 1530) used by some drones, as well as a "2.8K" (2880 × 1620).
[src:xbox-one/28nm] The **"28 nm" lithography process** is a half-node semiconductor manufacturing process based on a die shrink of the "32 nm" lithography process.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] Since at least 1997, "process nodes" have been named purely on a marketing basis, and have no direct relation to the dimensions on the integrated circuit; neither gate length, metal pitch or gate pitch on a "28 nm" device is twenty-eight nanometers.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company has offered "28 nm" production using high-K metal gate process technology.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] GlobalFoundries offers a "28 nm" foundry process called the "28SLPe" ("28 nm Super Low Power") foundry process, which uses high-K metal gate technology.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] According to a 2016 presentation by Sophie Wilson, 28 nm has the lowest cost per logic gate.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] Cost per gate had decreased as processes shrunk until reaching 28 nm, and has slowly risen since then.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] "28 nm" requires twice the number of design rules for ensuring reliability in manufacturing as "80 nm".
[src:xbox-one/28nm] AMD's Radeon HD 7970 uses a graphics processing unit manufactured using a "28 nm" process.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] Some models of the PS3 use an RSX 'Reality Synthesizer' chip manufactured using a "28 nm" process.
[src:xbox-one/28nm] FPGAs produced with "28 nm" process technology include models of the Xilinx Artix 7 FPGAs and Altera Cyclone V FPGAs.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The **32X** is an add-on for the Sega Genesis video game console.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Codenamed "Project Mars", it was designed to expand the power of the Genesis and serve as a transitional console into the 32-bit era until the release of the Sega Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X uses its own ROM cartridges and has its own library of games.
[src:xbox-one/32x] It was distributed under the name **Super 32X** in Japan and South Korea, **Genesis 32X** in North America, **Mega 32X** in Brazil, and **Mega Drive 32X** in all other regions.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega unveiled the 32X at the Consumer Electronics Show in June 1994, and presented it as a low-cost option for 32-bit games.
[src:xbox-one/32x] It was developed in response to the Atari Jaguar and concerns that the Saturn would not make it to market by the end of 1994.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Though the 32X was conceived as a new, standalone console, at the suggestion of Sega of America executive Joe Miller and his team, it became an add-on for the Genesis that made the console more powerful.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The final design contained two 32-bit central processing units and a visual display processor.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X failed to attract third-party developers and consumers because of the announcement of the Saturn's simultaneous release in Japan.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega's efforts to rush the 32X to market cut into time for game development, resulting in a weak library of 40 games that did not fully use the hardware, including Genesis ports.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega produced 800,000 32X units and sold an estimated 665,000 by the end of 1994, selling the rest at steep discounts until it was discontinued in 1996 as Sega turned its focus to the Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X is considered a commercial failure.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Initial reception was positive, highlighting the low price and power expansion to the Genesis.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Later reviews, both contemporary and retrospective, were mostly negative because of its limited game library, poor market timing and its market fragmentation of the Genesis.
[src:xbox-one/32x] By early 1994, Sega had started to become concerned about competition from newer, more powerful 32-bit consoles, such as the Atari Jaguar and the 3DO.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The Sega CD, a previous add-on for the Genesis, had not met commercial expectations, and the Genesis' successor, the Sega Saturn, would not be fully rolled out worldwide until late 1995.
[src:xbox-one/32x] This left a nearly two-year gap that Sega worried would allow its competitors to gain traction.
[src:xbox-one/32x] According to former Sega of America CEO Tom Kalinske, in regards to discussing the longevity of the Genesis, "Initially, the argument was that we could get another year of life out of the Genesis before we had to introduce the Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] During the Winter Consumer Electronics Show in January 1994, Sega of America research and development head Joe Miller took a phone call in his Las Vegas hotel suite from Sega president Hayao Nakayama, in which Nakayama stressed the importance of coming up with a quick response to the Atari Jaguar.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Included on this call were Sega of America producer Scot Bayless, Sega hardware team head Hideki Sato, and Sega of America vice president of technology Marty Franz.
[src:xbox-one/32x] One idea mooted by the Japanese team, referred to by former Sega of America producer Michael Latham as "Genesis 2", was an entirely new independent console.
[src:xbox-one/32x] This would have been a new Genesis model with an upgraded color palette and some limited 3D capabilities thanks to integration of ideas from the development of the Sega Virtua Processor chip.
[src:xbox-one/32x] According to Latham, Miller dismissed an upgraded Genesis as "just a horrible idea.
[src:xbox-one/32x] If all you're going to do is enhance the system, you should make it an add-on.
[src:xbox-one/32x] If it's a new system with legitimate new software, great.
[src:xbox-one/32x] From these discussions, the new add-on, codenamed "Project Mars", was advanced.
[src:xbox-one/32x] With Miller pushing for his American team to create the system, the 32X was designed as a peripheral for the existing Genesis, expanding its power with two 32-bit SuperH-2 processors, the same as those that would be used in the Saturn but with a lower clock speed.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The SH-2 had been developed in 1993 as a joint venture between Sega and Japanese electronics company Hitachi.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The original design for the 32X add-on, according to Bayless, was created on a cocktail napkin, but Miller denied this.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In another account, Bayless claimed that Franz began designing the 32X on a hotel notepad, drawing two SH-2 processors with separate framebuffers.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Although the new unit was a stronger console than originally proposed, it was not compatible with Saturn games.
[src:xbox-one/32x] This was justified by Sega's statement that both platforms would run at the same time, and that the 32X would be aimed at players who could not afford the more expensive Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Bayless praised the potential of this system at this point, calling it "a coder's dream for the day" with its twin processors and 3D capabilities.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega of America headed up the development of the 32X, with some assistance from Sato's team in Japan.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Shortages of processors due to the same 32-bit chips being used in both the 32X and the Saturn hindered the development of the 32X, as did the language barrier between the teams in Japan and the United States.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Before the 32X was launched, the release date of the Saturn was announced for November 1994 in Japan, coinciding with the 32X's target launch date in North America.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega of America was tasked with marketing the 32X with the Saturn's Japan release occurring simultaneously.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Their answer was to describe the 32X as a "transitional device" between the Genesis and the Saturn; Bayless said this "just made us look greedy and dumb to consumers".
[src:xbox-one/32x] The unveiling of the 32X to the public came at the Summer Consumer Electronics Show in June 1994 in Chicago.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Promoted as the "poor man's entry into 'next generation' games", 32X was marketed for its US$159 price point as a less-expensive alternative to the Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] However, Sega would not answer as to whether or not a Genesis console equipped with a Sega CD and a 32X would be able to run Saturn software.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Trip Hawkins, founder of The 3DO Company, was willing to point out that it would not, stating, "Everyone knows that 32X is a Band-Aid.
[src:xbox-one/32x] It's not a 'next generation system.' It's fairly expensive.
[src:xbox-one/32x] It's hard to program for, and it's not compatible with the Saturn." In response to these comments, Sega executive Richard Brudvik-Lindner pointed out that the 32X would play Genesis games, and had the same system architecture as the Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In August of that year, *GamePro* highlighted the advantages of the upcoming add-on in its 32-bit processors and significantly lower price, noting that "[n]o doubt gotta-get-it-now gamers will spend the big bucks to grab Saturn or PlayStation systems and games from Japan.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Responding to concerns over the 32X being a stopgap, Kalinske said, "Saturn will be at a price point that will not make it a massmarket item.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X was released on November 21, 1994, in North America, in time for the holiday season that year.
[src:xbox-one/32x] As announced, it retailed for $159.99 without a pack-in game.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Demand among retailers was high, and Sega could not keep up with orders for the new system.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Over 1,000,000 orders had been placed for 32X units, but Sega had only managed to ship 600,000 units by January 1995.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In the United States, nearly 500,000 units were sold by Christmas 1994, exceeding Sega's initial sales projection.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Launching at about the same price as a Genesis console, the price of the 32X was less than half of what the Saturn's price would be at launch.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The European release came in November 1994, at a price of £169.99, and also experienced initial high demand.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega promised 12 games available at launch and 50 games due for release in 1995 from third-party developers.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Despite Sega's initial promises, only six games were available at its North American launch, including *Doom*, *Star Wars Arcade*, *Virtua Racing Deluxe*, and *Cosmic Carnage*.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Although *Virtua Racing* was considered strong, *Cosmic Carnage* "looked and played so poorly that reporters made jokes about it".
[src:xbox-one/32x] Games were available at a retail price of $69.95.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Advertising for the system included images of the 32X being connected to a Genesis console to create an "arcade system".
[src:xbox-one/32x] Japan received the 32X on December 3, 1994, two weeks after the launch of the Saturn in the region.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X launched in Brazil in March 1995.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Despite the lower price console's positioning as an inexpensive entry into 32-bit gaming, Sega had a difficult time convincing third-party developers to create games for the new system.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Top developers were already aware of the coming arrival of the Sega Saturn, Nintendo 64, and PlayStation, and did not believe the 32X would be capable of competing with any of those systems.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Not wanting to create games for an add-on that was "a technological dead-end", many developers decided not to make games for the system.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Problems plagued games developed in-house due to the 32X's quick development time.
[src:xbox-one/32x] According to Bayless, "games in the queue were effectively jammed into a box as fast as possible, which meant massive cutting of corners in every conceivable way.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Even from the outset, designs of those games were deliberately conservative because of the time crunch.
[src:xbox-one/32x] By the time they shipped they were even more conservative; they did nothing to show off what the hardware was capable of." Kalinske has said that Sega of America did not receive enough support from Japan in game development.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Development kits came out late, leaving little time for game development before the 32X release.
[src:xbox-one/32x] According to one developer, the 32X's hardware was significantly slower than the Saturn and lacked the capability for texture mapping.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Journalists were similarly concerned about Sega's tactic of selling two similar consoles at different prices and attempting to support both, likening Sega's approach to that of General Motors and segmenting the market for its consoles.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In order to convince the press that the 32X was a worthwhile console, Sega flew in journalists from all around the country to San Francisco for a party at a local nightclub.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The event featured a speech from Kalinske, live music with a local rapper, and 32X games on exhibition.
[src:xbox-one/32x] However, the event turned out to be a bust, as journalists attempted to leave the party due to its loud music and unimpressive games on display, only to find that the buses that brought them to the nightclub had just left and would not return until the scheduled end of the party.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Though the system had a successful launch, demand soon disappeared.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Over the first three months of 1995, several of the 32X's third party publishers, including Capcom and Konami, cancelled their 32X projects so that they could focus on producing games for the Saturn and PlayStation.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X failed to catch on with the public, and is considered a commercial failure.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega was supporting five different consoles before this—Saturn, Genesis, Game Gear, Pico, and the Master System—as well as the Sega CD and 32X add-ons.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sales estimates for the 32X stood at 665,000 units at the end of 1994.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Despite assurances from Sega that many games would be developed for the system, in early 1996, Sega finally conceded that it had promised too much out of the add-on and decided to discontinue the 32X in order to focus on the Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In September 1995, the retail price for the 32X dropped to $99, and later the remaining inventory was cleared out of stores at $19.95, with 800,000 units sold in total.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The Sega Neptune is an unproduced two-in-one Genesis and 32X console that Sega planned to release in winter 1996, with the retail price planned to be under $200.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In Sega’s 1995 official product catalog, the system was presented under the name "Genesis 32X System", reflecting Sega’s intention to market it as a fully integrated Genesis and 32X platform.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The console was featured as early as March 1995, with *Sega Magazine* stating that the unit "shows [Sega's] commitment to the hardware".
[src:xbox-one/32x] The same official catalog listed the system as compatible with the Sega-CD, which logically follows from its design as an integrated platform, meaning that both standard CD titles and CD 32X titles would have operated on the Neptune as well.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sega cancelled the Neptune in October 1995, expressing concern that releasing another hardware platform would dilute their marketing focus on the Saturn and place a sub-$200 hybrid system uncomfortably close to their 32-bit offering.
[src:xbox-one/32x] *Electronic Gaming Monthly* later used the Neptune as an April Fools' Day prank in its April 2001 issue, claiming that Sega had discovered a warehouse of unused Neptune units available for US$199 (equivalent to $361.84 in 2025).
[src:xbox-one/32x] Although often referred to as a prototype, the physical unit shown in promotional contexts was in fact a non-functional mock-up constructed from wood and plastic, used solely to illustrate the intended industrial design of the system.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X can be used only in conjunction with a Genesis system.
[src:xbox-one/32x] It is inserted into the system like a standard game cartridge.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The add-on requires its own separate power supply, a connection cable linking it to the Genesis, and an additional conversion cable for the original model of the Genesis.
[src:xbox-one/32x] As well as playing its own library of cartridges, the 32X is backwards-compatible with Genesis games, and can also be used in conjunction with the Sega CD to play games that use both add-ons.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X also came with a spacer so it would fit properly with the second model of the Genesis; an optional spacer was offered for use with the Sega Genesis CDX system, but ultimately never shipped due to risks of electric shock when the 32X and CDX were connected.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Installation of the 32X also requires the insertion of two included electromagnetic shield plates into the Genesis' cartridge slot.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X contains two Hitachi SH-2 32-bit RISC processors with a clock speed of 23 MHz, which Sega claimed would allow the system to work 40 times faster than a stand-alone Genesis.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Its graphics processing unit is capable of producing 32,768 colors and rendering 50,000 polygons per second, which provides a noticeable improvement over the polygon rendering of the Genesis.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X also includes 256 kilobytes of random-access memory (RAM), along with 256 kilobytes of video RAM.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Sound is supplied through a pulse-width modulation sound source.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Input/output is supplied to a television set via a provided A/V cable that supplies composite video and stereo audio, or through an RF modulator.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Stereo audio can also be played through headphones via a headphone jack on the attached Genesis.
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X library consists of 40 games, including six that required both the 32X and Sega CD.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Among them were ports of arcade games *After Burner*, *Space Harrier*, and *Star Wars Arcade*, a sidescroller with a hummingbird as a main character in *Kolibri*, and a 32X-exclusive *Sonic the Hedgehog* spinoff, *Knuckles' Chaotix*.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Several of the games released for the 32X are enhanced ports of Genesis games, including *NFL Quarterback Club* and *World Series Baseball '95*.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In a retrospective review of the console, *Star Wars Arcade* was considered the best game for the 32X by *IGN* for its cooperative play, soundtrack, and faithful reproduction of the experiences of *Star Wars*.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In a separate review, *IGN*'s Levi Buchanan praised the 32X game *Shadow Squadron* as superior to *Star Wars Arcade*.
[src:xbox-one/32x] *Retro Gamer* writer Damien McFerran, however, praised *Virtua Fighter* as "the jewel in the 32X's crown", and *GamesRadar+* named *Knuckles' Chaotix* as the best game for the system.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In response to fan inquiries, Sega stated that the 32X architecture was not powerful enough to handle a port of *Virtua Fighter 2*.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Despite its 32-bit processing and potential for better graphics and sound than the Genesis, most games did not take advantage of the 32X hardware.
[src:xbox-one/32x] *Doom* for the 32X received near-perfect reviews, but was later criticized as inferior to versions for the PC and the Atari Jaguar, with missing levels, poor graphics and audio, jerky movement, and windowed gameplay.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Franz believes few developers were willing to invest in designing games to work with the 32X's improved audio abilities.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Because of time limitations, game designs were intentionally conservative and did not show what the 32X hardware was able to do.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Another factor was the architecture of the 32X's dual processors and graphics processor having difficulty accessing RAM, leading to developers choosing to only use one processor for their games.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In an interview at the end of 1995, Sega vice president of marketing Mike Ribero insisted that Sega was not abandoning the 32X, but acknowledged that first-party support had been lackluster: "I won't lie to you, we screwed up with 32X.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Initial reception to the 32X and its games upon the launch of the add-on was positive.
[src:xbox-one/32x] By late 1995, feedback to the add-on had soured.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In its 1996 Buyer's Guide, *Electronic Gaming Monthly'*s four reviewers scored the add-on 3, 3, 3, and 2 out of 10, criticizing the game library and Sega's abandonment of the system in favor of the Saturn.
[src:xbox-one/32x] A review in *Next Generation* panned the 32X for its weak polygon processing, the tendency of developers to show off its capabilities with garishly colored games, and its apparent function as "simply a way of grabbing extra 1994 mind and market share while waiting for Saturn".
[src:xbox-one/32x] The review gave it one out of five stars.
[src:xbox-one/32x] *Game Players* assessed it as so much less powerful than the Saturn and PlayStation that its lower price could not be considered an enticement, and said that the vast majority of its games could have been done just as well on the Super NES.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Retrospectively, the 32X is widely criticized as having a shallow library with a lack of support and a poor idea in the wake of the release of the Sega Saturn in Japan.
[src:xbox-one/32x] According to Buchanan, "I actually thought the 32X was a better idea than the SEGA CD...
[src:xbox-one/32x] The 32X, while underpowered, at least advanced the ball.
[src:xbox-one/32x] In particular, the console's status as an add-on and poor timing after the announcement of the Saturn has been identified by reviewers as being responsible factors for fracturing the audience for Sega's video game consoles in terms of both developers and consumers.
[src:xbox-one/32x] *Allgame*'s Scott Alan Marriott states that "[e]very add-on whittled away at the number of potential buyers and discouraged third-party companies from making the games necessary to boost sales." *GamePro* criticized the concept of the add-on, noting the expenses involved in purchasing the system.
[src:xbox-one/32x] According to reviewer Blake Snow, "Just how many 16-bit attachments did one need?
[src:xbox-one/32x] I think the 32X killed the idea of an add-on like this—a power booster—permanently.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Former executives at Sega have mixed opinions of the 32X.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Bayless believed firmly that the 32X served as a warning to the video game industry not to risk splintering the market for consoles by creating add-ons, and was critical of the Kinect and PlayStation Move for doing so.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Franz placed the 32X's commercial failure on its inability to function without an attached Genesis and lack of a CD drive, despite its compatibility with the Sega CD.
[src:xbox-one/32x] Miller remembered the 32X and his vision for the console positively, but conceded that the timing was wrong with the Saturn on the horizon.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Bungie was a video game developer working on their next project when they were acquired by Microsoft in 2000.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Their in-development game, *Halo: Combat Evolved*, turned into a launch title for Microsoft's Xbox console.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Bungie and Microsoft's cultures never meshed, and after the release of *Halo 2* Bungie began renegotiating for better profit sharing for their next game, *Halo 3*.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] These discussions led to Bungie announcing its independence from Microsoft in 2007.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] While Bungie was still contracted to deliver new *Halo* games, the rights to the franchise remained with Microsoft.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Xbox general manager Bonnie Ross recalled that her colleagues felt *Halo* was a waning property and looked at contracting an outside company to produce new games; the series's deep backstory and universe appealed to Ross, and she argued for a different approach.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Ross' pitch won over Microsoft Game Studios general manager Shane Kim, and she was put in charge of a new internal *Halo* studio, 343 Industries, named after the *Halo* character 343 Guilty Spark.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] 343 Industries started with a staff of roughly a dozen people in late 2007.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Bungie staffer Frank O'Connor assisted in the transition, and left Bungie to serve as 343 Industries' franchise director.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Ross' vision for *Halo* also impressed Microsoft art director Kiki Wolfkill, who joined the team as a studio head.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] During the transition, 343 Industries worked with the company Starlight Runner to compile a centralized story bible for the universe.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] In July 2009, 343 Industries announced it was working on a seven-part *Halo* anime series called *Halo Legends*.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Later that year the studio created Halo Waypoint, a downloadable application that tracks a user's *Halo* accomplishments.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] 343 Industries also increased staff for *Halo* development, recruiting staff from the defunct Pandemic Studios.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] 343 Industries also collaborated with Certain Affinity on *Halo: Reach*'s map packs.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Wanting to mark the occasion of *Halo: Combat Evolved*'s tenth anniversary, 343 Industries contracted Saber Interactive to develop *Halo: Combat Evolved Anniversary*, which released on November 15, 2011.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Following Bungie's completion of their last Halo title, *Halo: Reach*, 343 Industries was eventually given complete control of the *Halo* franchise including servers and data on March 31, 2012.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] The studio's development of *Halo 4*, which began in 2009, was completed in September.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] It was released on November 6, 2012, as the first title of a new *Halo* Reclaimer Trilogy which would include at least two more installments over the years.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] At E3 2013, Microsoft and 343 Industries announced the next "Halo" installment set for release on the Xbox One.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Shortly after the announcement, the Reclaimer Trilogy was confirmed by Microsoft Studios corporate vice-president Phil Spencer to be expanded into a Reclaimer Saga.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] The following year at E3 2014, the official title was revealed as "Halo 5: Guardians" along with plans for its release on October 27, 2015.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Microsoft, in a contract with Mega Bloks, is in conjunction with 343 Industries to manufacture a new line of toys and other memorabilia for the upcoming *Halo* saga.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] *Halo 5: Guardians* was released on October 27, 2015, with semi-exclusive content to those who purchased select Mega Bloks sets.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] 343 Industries has since released free monthly content updates since Halo 5's launch.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] At E3 2018, Microsoft Studios and 343 Industries announced the next *Halo* game, titled *Halo Infinite*, which was originally scheduled to launch in holiday 2020 for Xbox One and Windows PCs, in addition to being a launch title for the next Xbox console, the Xbox Series X.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] However, the game was delayed to release in 2021, in part due to the COVID-19 pandemic forcing the 343 staff to switch to remote work.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] *Infinite* was developed using 343's in-house Slipspace Engine.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] After *Infinite*'s release, 343 Industries supported the game via updates.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] On September 12, 2022, Bonnie Ross announced she would step down as studio head.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Following her departure, her responsibilities were split into three positions.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Pierre Hintze took over as studio head, Bryan Koski became GM of the franchise and Elizabeth Van Wyck took over business and operations.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Amid wider layoffs in the tech industry and Microsoft, 343 Industries was heavily affected, and Bloomberg News reported the studio would be making large changes to its development structure going forward.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] In October 2024, 343 Industries announced a rebrand as Halo Studios, amid a shift to Unreal Engine 5 for future project development, moving away from Slipspace Engine.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] A *Halo Waypoint* blog post in early July 2025 confirmed that Halo Studios would reveal details on their first project in Unreal Engine 5 during that October's *Halo* World Championships.
[src:xbox-one/343-industries] Additional personnel were laid off of the studio in 2025 amid wider Microsoft layoffs, with sources reporting to *Engadget* dissatisfaction and tension at the studio.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The **Xbox One** is a home video game console developed by Microsoft.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Announced in May 2013, it is the successor to Xbox 360 and the third console in the Xbox series.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It was first released in North America, parts of Europe, Australia, and South America in November 2013 and in Japan, China, and other European countries in September 2014.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It is the first Xbox game console to be released in China, specifically in the Shanghai Free-Trade Zone.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft marketed the device as an "all-in-one entertainment system", hence the name "Xbox One".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] An eighth-generation console, it mainly competed against Sony's PlayStation 4 and Nintendo's Wii U and later the Nintendo Switch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Moving away from its predecessor's PowerPC-based architecture, the Xbox One marks a shift back to the x86 architecture used in the original Xbox; it features an Accelerated Processing Unit (APU) from AMD built around the x86-64 instruction set.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One's controller was redesigned over the Xbox 360's, with a redesigned body, D-pad, and triggers capable of delivering directional haptic feedback.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console places an increased emphasis on cloud computing, as well as social networking features and the ability to record and share video clips or screenshots from gameplay or livestream directly to streaming services such as Mixer and Twitch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Games can also be played off-console via a local area network on supported Windows 10 devices.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console can play Blu-ray Disc, and overlay live television programming from an existing set-top box or a digital tuner for digital terrestrial television with an enhanced program guide.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console optionally included a redesigned Kinect sensor, marketed as the "Kinect 2.0", providing improved motion tracking and voice recognition.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One received positive reviews for its controller design, multimedia features and quieter internals, but criticism was initially given to its user interface.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] A revised version replaced the original in 2016, called the Xbox One S, which has a smaller form factor and support for HDR10 high-dynamic-range video, as well as support for 4K video playback and upscaling of games from 1080p to 4K.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It was praised for its smaller size, its on-screen visual improvements, and its lack of an external power supply, but its regressions such as the lack of a native Kinect port were noted.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] A high-end model, named Xbox One X, was unveiled in June 2017 and released in November; it features upgraded hardware specifications and support for rendering games at 4K resolution.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The system was succeeded by the Xbox Series X and Series S consoles, which launched on November 10, 2020.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Production of all Xbox One consoles ceased at the end of that year.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One is the successor to Xbox 360, Microsoft's previous video game console, which was introduced in November 2005 as part of the seventh generation of video game consoles.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Over the years, the 360 had received a number of small hardware revisions to reduce the unit's size and improve its reliability.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In 2010, Microsoft's Chris Lewis stated that the 360 was about "halfway" through its lifecycle; this was aided by the introduction of the Kinect motion sensor that year, which Lewis stated would extend the lifecycle by five years.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Initial hardware for the 360's successor, commonly referred to by the industry as the "Xbox 720", was reportedly under development as early as May 2011.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The official developer kit was codenamed Durango, and appeared to be available to developers by mid-2012.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Prior to the official unveiling, a rumor had circulated that the next Xbox console would be an "always on" system requiring a persistent Internet connection, though Microsoft had not confirmed this.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Orth's message drew further ire towards Microsoft, with concerns about digital rights management and practices against the sale of used games with an "always on" unit.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Orth opted to leave Microsoft a few days later due to the backlash.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Despite Microsoft's statements following the situation, denying the rumors, the mood it created lingered over the next several months.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In a press conference on May 21, 2013, the new console was publicly unveiled under the name Xbox One and was presented as an all-in-one home entertainment device.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The event focused heavily on the device's multimedia capabilities, demonstrating integration with television for over 30 minutes before any video games were shown.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In a 2019 interview, Phil Spencer, head of Xbox at Microsoft, recalled that this approach not only confused consumers about the intent of the Xbox One, but also Microsoft employees who had been working on the console.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Spencer stated that several employees complained to him about the presentation "blow[ing] up all the good work that [they]'ve done by talking about the product in a way that's not really matching what the soul of an Xbox console is about and what [their] customers are looking for from [Microsoft]".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] As a result of the negative feedback from the May presentation, the press event for E3 2013 focused on the video game functionality of the Xbox One first and foremost; Don Mattrick, then Microsoft's president of Interactive Entertainment Business, described the event as "all about the games".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] At the event, Microsoft announced that the console would be released in 21 different markets on November 22, 2013, but this was later amended down to 13.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The change, which pushed the release date for the other eight markets to 2014, was attributed to unforeseen complexity in localizing the device's voice recognition capabilities.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In September 2014, the Xbox One was released in 26 markets, including remaining markets in Europe, the Japanese market, and Middle Eastern markets.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft initially announced a different game licensing scheme for Xbox One than what was used upon its release: all games, including those purchased at retail, would be bound to the user's Xbox Live account.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Users could access their purchased games from any other Xbox One console, play games without their disc once installed, and allow users to "share" their games with up to ten designated "family" members.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] If a publisher allowed a game to be traded or resold, users could do this at "participating retailers", and could also transfer a game directly to any Xbox Live friend who had been on their list for at least 30 days, but only once per game.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] To synchronize licenses, the console would be required to connect to the internet once every 24 hours; if the console could not connect, all games would be disabled until the console was connected again.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Reaction to this digital rights management scheme was extremely negative in light of the previous concerns about the "always on" console from earlier in the year.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Critics felt that the changes would infringe on consumers' first-sale rights for games purchased on physical media, as games would only be licensed to users rather than sold, and the disc itself would only be used to install the game and not confer ownership of its license or permission to resell.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft also stated that game publishers would decide whether the physical copies of their games would be eligible for resale, and could impose restrictions or activation fees on second-hand copies of games.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In addition, loaning or renting games would not be possible at the console's launch, and Microsoft was "exploring the possibilities" with its partners.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] On June 19, 2013, shortly after E3 2013, Microsoft announced (in response to the negative reaction) that it would change its Xbox One DRM policy and game licensing model and reverse course.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] As with the Xbox 360, users would be able to share and resell physical games without restrictions, and beyond a mandatory software update upon the console's initial setup process to enable playback of Blu-ray and DVD video, the console would not require a permanent internet connection to operate.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] These changes required the family sharing features, along with the ability to play games without their disc after installation, to be dropped.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One chief product officer Marc Whitten stated that the family sharing feature may return in the future, but could not be implemented on launch due to time restraints.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Don Mattrick, then president of Microsoft's Interactive Entertainment Business, stated that the licensing changes were in response to the negative public reaction.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Other analysts believed the change was in direct response to Sony's aggressive position during its E3 conference.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] On July 1, 2013, Mattrick, who had been a leader in development on the Xbox One, announced his departure from Microsoft to become CEO of Zynga.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Analysts speculated that his departure was predicated on the poor response and subsequent reversal of the plans for Xbox One.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft also backtracked on a similarly controversial requirement for the Kinect sensor to be plugged into the Xbox One at all times for it to function.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Privacy advocates argued that Kinect sensor data could be used for targeted advertising and to perform unauthorized surveillance on users.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In response to these claims, Microsoft reiterated that Kinect voice recognition and motion tracking can be disabled by users, that Kinect data cannot be used for advertising under its privacy policy, and that the console would not redistribute user-generated content without permission.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Alongside the above changes, the Xbox One did not require the Kinect to be plugged in to operate by launch, though the initial bundles still included the Kinect device.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In 2015, four members of an international hacking group pleaded guilty to gaining unauthorized access to Microsoft's computer network and obtaining sensitive information relating to Xbox One and Xbox Live.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] At the time of the security breach, Microsoft was in the development stage for its next-generation gaming system.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Between 2011 and 2013, the hackers spent hundreds of hours searching through Microsoft's network copying log-in credentials, source code, technical specifications, and other data.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Group members say they were driven by an immense curiosity about Microsoft's then-unreleased Xbox One console and associated software.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] "Using stolen access credentials", two of the hackers also committed a physical theft by entering "a secure building on Microsoft's Redmond Washington campus" and carrying away three "Durango" development kits.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] On June 13, 2016, during its E3 2016 press conference, Microsoft unveiled **Xbox One S**, a revision of the original Xbox One hardware with a streamlined form factor and support for HDR10 and 4K video.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One S replaced the original launch hardware which had been discontinued around the same time.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft also teased a high-end version of Xbox One with upgraded hardware codenamed "Project Scorpio", which was unveiled and released the following year as **Xbox One X**.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft unveiled the **Xbox One S All-Digital Edition** on April 16, 2019, which included three digital games, *Forza Horizon 3*, *Sea of Thieves*, and *Minecraft*.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console does not have a physical disc drive, and all games must be downloaded.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It is $50 cheaper than the Xbox One S at $249 and was made available on May 7, 2019.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft ended production of the Xbox One family throughout 2020 in preparation for production of future hardware.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The original Xbox One's exterior casing consists of a two-tone "liquid black" finish; with half finished in a matte grey, and the other in a glossier black.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The matte side of the top of the console consists of a large air vent.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The design was intended to evoke a more entertainment-oriented and simplified look than previous iterations of the console; among other changes, the LED rings used by Xbox 360 are replaced by a glowing white Xbox logo used to communicate the system's status to the user.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Due to the overall ventilation design of the console, the original Xbox One is designed to only sit horizontally.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One S utilizes a refreshed version of this design, with a case that is 40% smaller in size and supports vertical orientation with a stand.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The main Xbox One S SKU is colored in an entirely matte "Robot White" finish, with half of the console adorned with machined holes, and a visible circular vent on top of the console's right half.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One is powered by an AMD "Jaguar" Accelerated Processing Unit (APU) with two quad-core modules totaling eight x86-64 cores clocked at 1.75 GHz, and 8 GB of DDR3 RAM with a memory bandwidth of 68.3 GB/s.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The APU is built on TSMC's 28nm process.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The memory subsystem also features an additional 32 MB of "embedded static" RAM, or ESRAM, with a memory bandwidth of 109 GB/s.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] For simultaneous read and write operations, the ESRAM is capable of a theoretical memory bandwidth of 192 GB/s and a memory bandwidth of 133 GB/s has been achieved with operations that involved alpha transparency blending.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The system includes a non-replaceable hard drive and a Blu-ray Disc optical drive.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] 138 GB of hard drive space is used by the operating system, with the remainder available for the storage of games.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Since the June 2014 software update, up to two USB drives can be connected to Xbox One to expand its capacity.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] External drives must support USB 3.0 and have a capacity of at least 256 GB.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It was reported that 3 GB of RAM would be reserved for the operating system and utility software, leaving 5 GB for games.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] With DirectX 11.2 as the console's API, the graphics processing unit (GPU) is based on an AMD GCN architecture with 12 compute units, which have a total of 768 cores, running at 853 MHz providing an estimated peak theoretical power of 1.31 TFLOPS.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] For networking, Xbox One supports Gigabit Ethernet, 802.11n wireless, and Wi-Fi Direct.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The original Xbox One supports 1080p and 720p video output; unlike the Xbox 360, the Xbox One does not support 1080i and other interlaced resolutions.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One supports HDMI 1.4 for both input and output, and does not support composite or component video.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One supports 7.1 surround sound, Dolby Atmos, and DTS:X.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One S additionally supports 2160p (4K resolution) video output, and high dynamic range (HDR) color using HDR10 (with a future update to add Dolby Vision HDR support for streaming video).
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The GPU on Xbox One S has a higher clock speed and ESRAM bandwidth than the original model, which can provide some performance improvements on games with dynamic resolution scaling (DRS) or uncapped frame rates.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console can monitor its internal temperature and adjust accordingly to prevent overheating; alongside increasing fan speed, additional measures can be taken, including throttling the hardware to a low-power state—a feature that was not present on Xbox 360.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Restricting power consumption lowers maximum performance, but the setting would be intended as a last resort to prevent permanent hardware damage.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox Wireless Controller maintains the overall layout found in the Xbox 360's controller, but with various refinements to its form.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Among its changes include a smoother form, textured analog sticks, a four-way directional pad, and redesigned triggers and shoulder buttons with a curved shape for ergonomics.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] "Menu" and "View" buttons have replaced the Start and Back buttons.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Each trigger features independent rumble motors called "Impulse Triggers", which allows developers to program directional vibration.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] One trigger can be made to vibrate when firing a gun, or both can work together to create feedback that indicates the direction of an incoming hit.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The controller also contains light emitters that allow it to be tracked and paired using the Kinect sensor, and to detect when it's not being held to automatically enter a low-power state.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] An updated revision of the controller was released in June 2015, which includes a 3.5-millimeter headphone jack and other minor changes.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] A third revision was introduced alongside and first bundled with Xbox One S, with textured grips and Bluetooth support.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox Wireless Controller includes a micro USB port; when attached via a micro-USB cable, the controller can operate without battery power and can charge remotely, and is supported on computers running Windows 7 or later with drivers.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One Wireless Adapter accessory allows wireless use of Xbox One controllers on Windows computers also running Windows 7 or later.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Elite Wireless Controller was released in October 2015.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It was described and marketed as "an elite controller for the elite gamer", containing interchangeable parts, "hair trigger locks" for the triggers that allow users to reduce the amount of distance they must be pressed to register a press, and software for remapping buttons.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In May 2018, Microsoft announced the Xbox Adaptive Controller—a special controller designed for users with disabilities.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It features two large dome-like buttons, and a series of connectors corresponding to standard Xbox controller buttons—which are used to attach specific types of buttons and other assertive peripherals.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The controller can also be used in conjunction with Copilot—a feature introduced in 2017 that allows multiple controllers to be used in tandem on behalf of a single player.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] As of the November 2018 update, developers may now optionally allow their titles to support computer mice and keyboards as input.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft also unveiled an exclusive partnership with Razer Inc. to produce a specific line of Xbox-optimized keyboard and mice peripherals, with Xbox system keys and support for Razer's Chroma LED lighting platform.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Kinect 2.0, an updated natural user interface sensor, was redesigned and recreated to provide motion-tracking and voice commands for the Xbox One.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Kinect 2.0 features a wide-angle time-of-flight camera and a 1080p camera, in comparison to the VGA resolution of the Xbox 360 version, and processes 2 GB of data per second to map its environment.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Kinect 2.0 has an improved accuracy over its predecessor; it can track up to 6 people simultaneously, referred to as "skeletons", perform heart rate tracking, track controller gestures, and read QR codes to redeem Xbox Live gift cards.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] By default, voice recognition is active at all times, so the console can receive voice commands from the user, even when the console is in sleep mode.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] It is possible to wake the console with a command, although settings are available to change which individual Kinect functions are active.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Prior to and after the mandate, all Xbox One consoles initially shipped with the Kinect sensor included.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] On June 9, 2014, cheaper Xbox One bundles were introduced, which did not include the Kinect sensor.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft stated the decision to offer Xbox One bundles without Kinect was to "[offer] a choice to people that would allow people to buy an Xbox One and then ramp up to Kinect when they can afford to", while also allowing games to use processing power that was previously reserved for Kinect.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] An updated Xbox Development Kit issued in June 2014 allows developers to explicitly disable motion tracking functionality in games, allowing access to additional system resources that represent about 10% of the GPU processing power.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] These resources were previously reserved for Kinect skeletal tracking, regardless of whether the Kinect sensor was attached or in use.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] A Windows compatible Kinect 2.0 was released on July 15, 2014.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Kinect 2.0 was released as a standalone and optional item in October 2014; it is bundled with a digital copy of *Dance Central Spotlight*.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One S lacks the Kinect connection port, requiring a USB/power adapter to use the accessory.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] A free USB adapter was provided by Microsoft to Kinect owners who registered their ownership of Kinect and Xbox One S online up until March 2017.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The adapter was sold separately thereafter but has since been discontinued.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Kinect for Xbox One was officially discontinued on October 25, 2017.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One runs two operating systems within a hypervisor; games run within one separate operating system, while apps and the user interface run within a stripped-down version of Microsoft Windows; the original system software was based on Windows 8, but it has since been changed to Windows 10.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] This architecture allows resources to be allocated specifically to different aspects of the console's functions, including multitasking and Kinect processing, ensuring an "absolute guarantee of performance" for games.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One supports Universal Windows Platform apps, which can be designed to run across Xbox One, Windows 10, and Windows 10 Mobile in synchronization with the Windows platform.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One's user interface uses Microsoft's Fluent Design System; previous iterations of the console's software used the Metro design language.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The dashboard is divided into "Home", "Mixer", "Community", "Entertainment", and "Store" sections, with the "Home" page further divided into "blocks" that can display pinned games/apps, as well as other content.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Pressing the Xbox Guide button opens a sidebar with access to common functions such as the friends list, apps, the user's party, and settings.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Users can go back to the dashboard while using games or apps using either the Xbox button on their controller or a voice command; up to four apps can run (either actively or in the background) at once, but only one game can run at a time.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Use of Kinect enables the ability to control the console via voice commands.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One's voice control capabilities are similar to, albeit richer than those of Xbox 360.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The voice assistant Cortana was added in 2016 to provide expanded voice command functionality with natural language recognition.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The dashboard originally used a layout similar to Windows 8's "Start screen", with a horizontal-scrolling, tile-based interface.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] This design was replaced for Xbox Preview Program members in September 2015 with the current interface, known as "the New Xbox One Experience", which was publicly released as part of the November 12, 2015, system update.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Alongside its new layout, support for Kinect motion controls on the dashboard were removed.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The UI was refreshed again in April 2017, adding the new Guide sidebar and other new features.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] At this time, the ability to "snap" apps as a sidebar for multi-tasking was removed.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The UI was further revamped in October 2017, adopting Windows 10's "Fluent" design language. and adds a light color option for the console's user interface.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In 2024, it was reported that original Xbox One models operating on firmware versions prior to 2019 were experiencing update failures, which led to the disablement of the majority of the console's functions due to mandatory online requirements.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft fixed the issue shortly after.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The issue raised concerns regarding the preservation status of the console and its game library.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox One can view and play content from DLNA servers and USB storage devices using the "Media Player" app.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] An application allows playback of video from Blu-ray Disc, DVD and CD media.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console provides the ability to feed live television by serving as an HDMI pass-through for an existing television provider's set-top box or an optional Digital TV Tuner accessory that allows use of digital terrestrial television.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console provided its own electronic program guide known as OneGuide, augmenting the existing streaming functionality to provide show recommendations based on viewing history, integrated access to "App Channels" corresponding to online video services, and voice control via Kinect.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The set-top box and television were controlled by OneGuide using an IR blaster.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] OneGuide service was discontinued in May 2021.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The digital TV tuner accessory allows limited DVR functionality for pausing and rewinding live TV for up to 30 minutes.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The Xbox Live service has been scaled up to use 300,000 servers for Xbox One users.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Cloud storage is available to save music, films, games and saved content, and developers are able to use Live servers (along with the Microsoft Azure cloud computing platform) to offer dynamic in-game content and other functionality.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The December 2016 software update added the new social networking feature Clubs, which allows users to join groups focused on specific interests or games, and Looking for group (LFG), a system to help users locate players to join their party for multiplayer play.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Players can use the Upload Studio app to edit and share clips from the last five minutes of gameplay footage that is automatically recorded by the console.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Games can also be developed so that recording can automatically be triggered in response to notable events, such as achievements.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One supports streaming directly to the service Twitch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Users can use voice commands to immediately begin streaming footage of their current game directly to the service, and use Kinect's camera and microphone to record video and audio narration.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Users can feature recorded clips on their Xbox Live profile page in a "Showcase" section.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The console had also supported Mixer prior to its shutdown in July 2020.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] As with Xbox 360, premium online features such as multiplayer, voice communication, broadcasting and Upload Studio require an Xbox Live Gold subscription to use.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Unlike Xbox 360, a user's Xbox Live Gold subscription benefits apply to all other users of their designated "home" console as well, rather than requiring a separate subscription for each user.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Since June 2014, applications no longer require an Xbox Live Gold membership to use.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Additional subscriptions for outside services such as Netflix may still be required.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft also extended its Games with Gold program to Xbox One, providing Xbox 360 and Xbox One games to Xbox Live Gold subscribers on a monthly basis.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] An updated Windows 10 version of the app's PC version introduced the ability to stream games from the console to PCs over a local network.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] An Xbox One controller must be used, but Windows-compatible headsets and microphones can be used for voice chat.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Games requiring Kinect are not supported, while Game DVR and online streaming are not available while using this feature The feature later became available to the Xbox mobile apps as well, now known as "Remote Play".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox One games are distributed physically on Blu-ray Disc, and digitally as downloads through Microsoft Store (formerly Xbox Games Store).
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] All Xbox One games must be installed to the console's storage: one can begin to play portions of a game (such as opening levels) once the installation or download reaches a specific point, while the remainder of the game is downloaded or installed in the background.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] However, for older titles (such as Xbox 360 games, see "Xbox 360 compatibility", below), one must wait until installation is completed to play.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Updates to games and system software are also downloaded in the background and while in standby.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] If the game is installed from physical media, the disc is still required for validation purposes.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] If the game is installed on another console, and that console owner no longer has access to the disc, the owner has the option of unlocking the install on their hard drive by purchasing it through Xbox Live; the installed game then acts as a game installed on the hard drive.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] An active internet connection may be required for some games, particularly those that rely on server-side processing.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft introduced an Early access program known as Xbox Game Preview in 2015, which allows developers to launch unfinished games for consumers to purchase and beta test before its official launch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In 2016, Microsoft began to make future Xbox One-exclusive first-party releases simultaneously available on Windows 10 PCs, with digital cross-buy support via Microsoft Store under the branding Xbox Play Anywhere.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] This, thus, makes the games Microsoft platform exclusives rather than Xbox One exclusives.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft has used the branding "console launch exclusive" to refer to titles (such as *PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds*) that are timed or permanent exclusives to Xbox console hardware, but were already available on, or are planned to be available on PC.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In February 2017, Microsoft introduced an "on-demand" subscription service known as Xbox Game Pass, separate from Xbox Live Gold, which allows users to download and play games from its library for the life of the subscription.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In April 2019, Microsoft also introduced Xbox Game Pass Ultimate, which bundles Game Pass with an Xbox Live Gold subscription.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] At its launch, the Xbox One did not have native backward compatibility with original Xbox or Xbox 360 games, and at the time Microsoft stated it had no plans for any form of backward compatibility on the console.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Don Mattrick, head of the company's Interactive Entertainment Business at the time, said in an interview that he didn't see backward compatibility as a problem and stated that "If you're backwards compatible, you're backwards".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] According to Mattrick, investing in backward compatibility wasn't worth the company's time and resources, as only 5% of Microsoft's customers played older games on new video game consoles.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] However, backward compatibility had been a planned launch feature by Microsoft and had been actively under development as early as 2007 under the "Trioxide" program to get Xbox 360 code to run on 64-bit hardware.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Following criticism of its plan for an "always on" console from the May 2013 announcement, Microsoft had to put significant effort to prepare the Xbox One software for a revised approach, and the backward compatibility development work was put on hold.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Interim solutions were suggested: senior project management and planning director Albert Penello explained that Microsoft was initially considering a cloud gaming platform to enable backward compatibility, but he felt it would be "problematic" due to varying internet connection qualities.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox Live director of programming Larry "Major Nelson" Hryb did state that users could theoretically use the HDMI-in port on the console to pass an Xbox 360 (or, alternatively, any other device that supports HDMI output, including competing consoles) through the Xbox One.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] This process does generate a small amount of unnoticeable display lag.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Following the release of the Xbox One and transition of Phil Spencer to the head of the Xbox division in 2014, he and software engineering vice president Kareem Choudhry restarted the backward compatibility program in relative secret within the company.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Choudhry brought on previous engineers that worked on Trioxide, including Kevin La Chapelle, Jonathan Morrison, and Barry Bond, to restart the program.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The team chose to start with *Castle Crashers*, which included Xbox networking features, to test backward compatibility.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] *Castle Crashers* frequently crashed to a screen with alphanumeric codes, which La Chapelle was able to obtain from the game's developers, The Behemoth, which helped them to rapidly diagnose problems and fix the compatibility issues.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Solving most of the major problems through *Castle Crashers*, the background compatibility team decided to let the program be announced at E3 2015 with plans to have one hundred titles available by the end of 2015.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] However, by E3, they still found problems with some games running at extremely low framerates.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] During the event, Morrison recognized that a fundamental difference between the Xbox 360 and Xbox One was its scheduling rate, and when they returned, Morrison's idea helped them to rapidly complete work to meet its promised goal by the end of that year.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox 360 backward compatibility uses "Fission", a software emulator within the system software; 104 Xbox 360 titles were supported at the feature's public launch, with more added in the following months.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox 360 games contained within *Rare Replay* are packaged as standalone applications using the Xbox 360 emulation.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft stated that publishers would only need to provide permission to the company to allow the repackaging, and it expected the number of supported games to increase significantly over time.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft, along with fourteen other third-party publishers, will offer supported games, and all Games with Gold titles on Xbox 360 since November 2015 are made compatible.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] On June 10, 2019, Microsoft stated that it had wound down the addition of new titles to the backward compatibility program in order to focus on Xbox One's successor, the Xbox Series X/S console, which was released in November 2020.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft announced one last set of additions to the backward compatibility program on November 15, 2021, as part of their 20th anniversary of the Xbox, adding 76 titles new to the program.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] However, Microsoft anticipated this will be the last set of backward compatible titles they can add, as they "have reached the limit of our ability to bring new games to the catalog from the past due to licensing, legal and technical constraints".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] All Xbox 360 and original Xbox games that are supported by backward compatibility on the Xbox One are also supported on the Xbox Series X/S.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] In addition, these games include automatic high-dynamic-range rendering (HDR) and resolution increases, depending on the original game and current platform.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Select games have also been enabled with FPS Boost that increases the rendering rate up to 60 frames per second.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Xbox division head Phil Spencer had also hinted the possibility of adding support for games from the original Xbox.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] For the backward compatibility team, after they completed the framework for Xbox 360 compatibility so that other engineering teams could take over, they turned to the question of compatibility with the original Xbox console.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] The program was started in November 2016, under the code name "Fusion", and was led by software engineer Spencer Perreault.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Perreault initially tried the same approaches as the team had done with "Fission", but due to the differences in memory management sizes and chipset bit-rates, these initial tests failed.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Instead, Perreault worked to bring "Dolphin", a developer tool for the original Xbox, working to get its emulation correct.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] La Chapelle brought in a number of personal Xbox titles to test in Perreault's emulation, getting about a 10% "hit rate" on successes, though the variety of failures helped Perreault to identify common problems, and within a month, had improved the successful hit rate to about 90%.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] As with Xbox 360 backward compatibility, the Fusion emulation enables Xbox games to be scaled to 1080p resolutions, work with Xbox One networking features, and can allow mixed-console System Link connection between all three generations of Xbox.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] With Perreault's success, Microsoft announced the Xbox backward compatibility on the Xbox One in June 2017.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Thirteen titles were initially released on October 24, 2017.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft announced an additional 19 titles to be added to the Xbox One service during April 2018.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p01] Microsoft does not anticipate that there will be as many Xbox titles brought to the program as with the Xbox 360, primarily due to legal issues related to intellectual property, contracts, and companies that have since gone defunct.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] While the initial unveiling of the Xbox One in May 2013 created criticism that led to significant changes in the digital rights management scheme it would use, other features of the console were highlighted by journalists.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The editorial staff of *Game Informer* offered both praise and criticism for the console.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Matt Helgeson described the console as Microsoft's intent to "control the living room".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] He called Xbox One's instant switching features "impressive", and that the console was "a step in the right direction" with regards to TV entertainment, especially the prospect of avoiding the usage of non-intuitive user interfaces often found on cable set-top boxes.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Jeff Cork said that Microsoft had "some great ideas" for the console, but that it failed to properly communicate them.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Microsoft's E3 2013 press conference was criticized for focusing too much on games that, beyond increased graphical capabilities, provided experiences that were otherwise similar to previous-generation games—giving little incentive for buying the new console.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Rafi Mohammed, author of *The Art of Pricing*, felt that Microsoft priced Xbox One "too high" and that the $100 premium over its competitor could "derail" the system during the 2013 holiday season.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Upon its release, the Xbox One received favorable reviews from critics and reviewers.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In its launch review, *Polygon* gave the Xbox One a score of 8/10.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Its design was described as "inoffensive" but its larger size noted, while the console's quieter and cooler operation was praised for indicating a potentially higher reliability than Xbox 360 was on-launch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The controller was praised for its battery life and "premium" design, but some members of the site's staff felt that its shoulder buttons were stiffer than that of previous designs.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Ben Gilbert of *Engadget* was similarly modest upon its launch, assigning the console a score of 81/100 and describing the Xbox One's design as a "1993 artist's rendering of 2013's technology".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Acknowledging that its controller was a mere refinement of the "ubiquit[ous]" Xbox 360 design, he praised the controller for its improved D-pad and quieter triggers but criticized its stiff shoulder buttons.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The console was also panned for missing certain promised features on-launch, such as Upload Studio, game streaming, and certain apps/services.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] There are oddities peppered throughout, which is the root for countless headaches and frustrations." Xbox One's in-game performance was mixed, with some titles showing slower performance over PS4, but some multi-platform games performing better on Xbox One than PS4.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] So while PlayStation might have the upper hand for now when it comes to certain third-party titles, it may not always remain that way.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Just how Microsoft will get it to that point, though, is still a mystery." However, he disfavored the console's dependence upon a subscription for most of its functionality, Kinect's voice recognition, and that some games do not natively run at 1080p resolution, but are upscaled.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In an August 2016 review of the Xbox One S model, *TechRadar* further commended Microsoft's recent improvements to Xbox One, citing a strong lineup of first-party titles in 2015 and further improvements to the console's interface.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The number of "hidden" options in Xbox One's user interface was equated to "hunting for treasure in a messy room"; as such, Kinect voice commands, in combination with access to common functions within the Xbox SmartGlass app, were praised for helping to provide a more streamlined user experience.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The Xbox One S revision was critically praised for its improvements over the original model, including its streamlined design, the addition of HDR and 4K video support, and visual improvements on some games (such as *Fallout 4* and *Rise of the Tomb Raider*) when upscaled to 4K.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Bohn concluded that the Xbox One S would appeal best to new owners or those who wish to leverage its HDR and 4K support but recommended that existing owners consider Xbox One X instead.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The Xbox One platform has faced criticism for lacking in exclusive releases over competitors such as PlayStation 4 and Nintendo Switch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] By contrast, the other consoles of the eighth generation, the PlayStation 4 and the Nintendo Switch, have seen a large number of critically successful first- and third-party exclusives.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Further, Activision signed with Sony Interactive Entertainment for timed exclusivity on certain add-on content in the *Call of Duty* and *Destiny* franchises, the former having replaced a previous deal with Microsoft.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Chaim Gartenberg of *The Verge* opined that "without unique games, the Xbox One is a slightly less powerful, definitely less popular PlayStation 4", while Rob Fahey of *GamesIndustry.biz* questioned whether the lack of Xbox exclusives was a sign of a "worrying trend" for the future of the platform.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Microsoft began a realignment of its first party studios then named Microsoft Studios starting around 2017.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The collection of studios was rebranded as Xbox Game Studios in February 2019, with a strong aim to provide exclusive games for the Xbox console family from these studios.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In addition to the pre-launch controversy over the required use of the Kinect device, the games that launched with the Xbox One that supported the Kinect were seen by critics as lackluster, and the only Kinect-exclusive game at launch, *Fighter Within*, was one of the system's worst-reviewed games.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Microsoft initially imposed policies referred to as the "parity clause" on indie games, which required that the Xbox One version of a game be released at the same time as versions on other platforms.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Phil Spencer stated that this rule was intended to ensure that Xbox One was a "first-class" platform by discouraging staggered releases.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] However, these policies resulted in some studios, such as Vlambeer (developer of *Nuclear Throne*) choosing to negotiate console exclusivity with Sony instead, who proved to be more receptive to indie development.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] By July 2015, Microsoft had changed its policies in response to the criticism, with Spencer admitting that this policy was onerous on smaller studios.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Spencer also stated that Microsoft was willing to work with studios to help make the Xbox launches of former timed exclusives "special in some way", so that customers are not simply purchasing "last year's game".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Microsoft only publicized its sales figures during the first year after release.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The last official figures were 3 million sold as of December 2013, and approximately 10 million shipped as of November 2014.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In October 2015 Microsoft announced that it would no longer publish sales figures for any of their systems.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On November 22, 2013, Microsoft confirmed that it had sold one million Xbox One consoles within its first 24 hours of being available.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] That figure rose to about 2 million units after 18 days of sale, and to 3 million units by the end of 2013.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In their Q2 2014 earnings report on January 23, 2014, Microsoft announced that 3.9 million Xbox One units had been shipped worldwide.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On April 17, 2014, Microsoft announced it had shipped 5 million consoles to retailers worldwide, with that figure rising to almost 10 million on November 12, 2014.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The company also revealed that a price cut had tripled U.S. sales of the console over the previous week.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In October 2015, Microsoft announced that it would no longer publish sales figures for the system, instead focusing on Xbox Live engagement figures.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The last official cumulative sales figure is from November 2014, at 10 million units sold.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] *GamesIndustry.biz'*s Brendan Sinclair speculated that this decision was to draw attention away from the lower sales figures of the Xbox One compared to the PlayStation 4, and estimated Xbox One sales to be around 18 million at the time.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In January 2016, CFO of Electronic Arts Blake Jorgensen reported during a financial call that the Xbox One had sold "around 18 to 19 million" units.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] This is half of the 36 million units of the PlayStation 4 that Sony claimed at the time, but higher than that of the Xbox One's other main competitor, Nintendo's Wii U, which sold 12.5 million units.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Research firm IHS Markit estimated 39.1 million units were sold by the end of March 2018.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Video game industry analyst Daniel Ahmad estimated that approximately 41 million units had been as of January 2019.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Most industry analysts have estimated Xbox One's lifetime sales to be around 50 million to 51 million units.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In an August 2022 antitrust filing with Brazilian regulator Cade regarding its proposed acquisition of Activision Blizzard, Microsoft stated that "more than twice as many" PlayStation 4 consoles were sold in comparison to Xbox consoles during the previous generation.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In June 2023, during an ID@Xbox presentation at the Best International Games (BIG) Festival in Brazil, Microsoft revealed that 58+ million Xbox One consoles have been shipped worldwide.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] By the end of 2013, 126,201 Xbox One consoles had been sold in France, according to GfK.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In 2015, 298,000 Xbox One consoles were sold in France, and total sales reached 715,000 units in the country.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The 1 million unit sold would be crossed by early 2017.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In 2015, 270,000 Xbox One consoles were sold in Germany, bringing total sales to 600,000 units.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One launch week sales were around 15,000 units in Spain, roughly equivalent to the Xbox 360's launch week.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One sales reached 428,000 units by the end of 2016, and topped 500,000 units by the end of 2017.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] 24,500 Xbox One consoles were sold in Spain in 2020.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Microsoft's consoles have historically struggled to gain significant market share in the country.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The Xbox One sold a total figure of 23,562 consoles within its launch week in September 2014, which is down compared to the Xbox 360's opening week sales of 62,000 consoles in December 2005.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Its best-selling titles were *Titanfall* at 22,416 units, *Kinect Sports Rivals* at 14,191 units, and *Dead Rising 3* at 7,330 units.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In the week ending June 14, 2015, the Xbox One sold just 100 consoles in Japan; in the same week the Wii U sold 16,413 consoles.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] According to the International Data Corporation, only 0.3% of the 46.9 million Xbox Ones sold worldwide through the second quarter of 2019 have been from Japan.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] As of December 2020, shortly after the release of Xbox Series X and Series S, Xbox One sales in Japan were estimated to be around 115,000 units according to *Famitsu*.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One launch week sales were around 150,000 units, double that of the Xbox 360.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Microsoft enacted a UK-only price cut in February 2014 to bring the console's price closer to that of the PlayStation 4, which had released at a more affordable price.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The Xbox One was the best-selling console in November 2014.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The Xbox One took 104 weeks to reach the 2 million units sold in the UK, generating £726m in revenue.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The launch of the revised Xbox One S and Xbox One X models, in August 2016 and November 2017, respectively, greatly improved sales of the system in the region.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Following the release of the Xbox One S, Xbox One sales were up 989% on a week-to-week basis.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] This boost in sales caused the Xbox One to be the best-selling console for two months in a row for the first time in the UK, in September and October 2016, with 99,496 units sold during the latter month.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] First-week sales of the Xbox One X in November 2017 reached 80,000 units.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Total Xbox One sales were approaching 5 million units near the end of 2018.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] During the week of Black Friday 2019, Xbox One was the best-selling console with over 100,000 units sold.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Demand for the Xbox One was strong in the US.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The US is sometimes referred by pundits as a "traditional Xbox market" alongside the UK and Australia, which are regions where Xbox systems tend to do particularly well.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Microsoft announced that the Xbox One had sold 909,132 units in November 2013, based on only nine days of sales.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The Xbox One launch in November 2013 was nearly three times that of the Xbox 360 launch in November 2005.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] An average of 2.1 games per console were sold.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Based on approximately 102,000 shopping receipts tracked by InfoScout, 1,500 of which included a purchase of either a video game or a video game console, the Xbox One was the highest-selling console during the Black Friday 2013 sales period in the United States.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One was the best-selling console in December 2013, selling 908,000 units.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] 258,000 Xbox One consoles were sold in the US in the month of February 2014.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In March 2014, hardware and software sales rose to 311,000 consoles and 1.4 million games sold, respectively.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] 115,000 Xbox One consoles were sold in April 2014.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In June 2014, following the introduction of an Xbox One bundle without the Kinect priced at $400, sales of the Xbox One more than doubled that of the previous month.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One was the best-selling console in the country in November and December 2014, in April and October 2015, and from July to October 2016.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] During the month of November 2018, over 1.3 million Xbox One consoles were sold in the US.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On launch, Xbox One was available in a single retail configuration, which included the console with 500 GB hard drive, one controller, and Kinect sensor.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In the United States, it retailed for US$499.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On June 9, 2014, Microsoft released a new Xbox One retail configuration that excludes the Kinect sensor, costing US$399.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] A standalone Kinect sensor for Xbox One for use with these models was released in October 2014, retailing at US$150.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On June 16, 2015, Microsoft lowered the price of the stock model to US$349, and released a new US$399 model containing a 1 terabyte hard drive and in some markets, *Halo: The Master Chief Collection*.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In May 2016, Microsoft lowered the price of selected 500 GB bundles to US$299, and 1 TB bundles to US$319 as a limited time offer of unspecified length.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On June 14, 2016, the price of 500 GB models was lowered once more to US$279 through October 2016, in anticipation of the launch of Xbox One S.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On August 31, 2015, Microsoft announced Xbox One Elite—a new SKU with a 1 TB solid-state hybrid drive and an Elite controller.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] It was released in November 2015 and retails for US$499.99.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In the US, the Elite bundle was a timed exclusive to GameStop and Microsoft Store.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The launch hardware configuration's production was discontinued by mid-2016.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Its launch price in the United Kingdom was £429, A$599 in Australia, JP¥49,980 in Japan.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] It also launched in China in July 2014, for CN¥3,699.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Those who pre-ordered Xbox One for its release received a special "Day One Edition", which featured a "DAY ONE 2013" inscriptions on the controller, and a unique achievement.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] A white "Launch Team" edition was given exclusively to Microsoft staff members, featuring the inscription "I made this, LAUNCH TEAM 2013" on the console and controller, and was bundled with *Dead Rising 3*, *Forza Motorsport 5*, *Ryse: Son of Rome*, and *Zoo Tycoon*.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] A similar limited edition was gifted to Respawn Entertainment employees following the release of *Titanfall*, with a black, white, and orange color scheme and a similarly styled controller inspired by the game (the controller itself would be released publicly as a tie-in).
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One consoles bundled with digital copies of specific games have also been released, including *Titanfall* and *Forza Motorsport 5*.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In August 2018, Microsoft announced that it would, for a limited time, offer a financing program known as **Xbox All Access** through Microsoft Store in the United States.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The program will allow users to purchase an Xbox One S or X console, bundled with subscriptions to both Xbox Live Gold and Xbox Game Pass, financed over a two-year contract.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The customer retains ownership of the console after the two years, and if they break the contract prior to that, they must pay the difference on the remaining console cost.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The pricing is set to be cheaper overall than purchasing the individual elements alone.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The **Xbox One S** is available in 500 GB, 1 TB, and a "special edition" 2 TB model, which originally retailed at US$299, $349, and $399 respectively.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The 2 TB model was released on August 2, 2016, and 1 TB and 500 GB models were released on August 23, 2016.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] A *Gears of War 4* special edition was also released.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On June 11, 2017, Microsoft lowered the prices of the 500 GB *Battlefield 1* and 1 TB *Forza Horizon 3* Xbox One S console bundles by US$50.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] At Gamescom 2017, Microsoft unveiled a 1 TB *Minecraft* limited edition, with a grass block-themed hardware and a Creeper-themed controller.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] During an Inside Xbox livestream in September 2018, Microsoft unveiled a 1 TB *Fortnite Battle Royale* bundle, with online codes to acquire unique in-game Eon-themed items and currency.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On October 9, 2018, Microsoft announced that they would be releasing a 1 TB *Minecraft Creators* bundle, with a download code for *Minecraft*, in-game currency, DLC packs, and a free trial for Xbox Game Pass and Xbox Live Gold.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On June 7, 2019, Microsoft released a second *Fortnite* bundle with purple hardware, as well as in-game currency and items.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On March 17, 2020, a similar *Roblox* bundle was released, bundled with in-game items and currency, and a one-month trial of Xbox Game Pass Ultimate.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The Xbox One S was quietly discontinued by the end of 2020.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] On April 16, 2019, Microsoft unveiled a configuration of the Xbox One S named **Xbox One S All-Digital Edition**, which does not include the Blu-ray Disc drive.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] It is a 1 TB model sold at a price of US$249, and includes digital download cards for *Forza Horizon 3*, *Minecraft*, and *Sea of Thieves*.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The console was released on May 7, 2019.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One X features upgraded hardware, designed primarily to render games at 4K resolution and to provide performance improvements for existing games; they can be displayed at full resolution on 4K displays or supersampled for lower-resolution displays.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] It uses a system-on-chip (SoC) known as *Scorpio Engine*, which incorporates a 2.3 GHz octa-core CPU, and a Radeon GPU with 40 compute units clocked at 1172 MHz, generating 6 teraflops of graphical computing performance.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] It also includes 12 GB of GDDR5 RAM with 9 GB allocated to games.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Scorpio Engine's CPU utilizes a custom platform designed to maintain compatibility with the Jaguar CPU of the original Xbox One, but with a 31% increase in performance; the custom platform is unrelated to AMD's current Ryzen architecture.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The console uses a vapor-chamber method of cooling for the SoC, and motherboards tailored to the exact voltage needs of each individual Scorpio SoC to optimize their output and energy usage.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] The console also supports AMD's FreeSync technology, 1440p resolution, and/or 120 Hz refresh rate on compatible displays.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One X is compatible with all existing Xbox One software and accessories, including the Xbox and Xbox 360 games that have been made backward-compatible.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] To assist in optimizing the new hardware to run existing games at 4K resolution, Microsoft developers used internal debugging software to collect GPU traces from major titles that did not run at full 1080p resolution on the original Xbox One.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] *Halo 5: Guardians*, which uses a scaling system that dynamically lowers the game's resolution when needed to maintain a consistent frame rate, was able to run at its native resolution with no scaling on Xbox One X hardware.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Phil Spencer touted that Xbox One X's hardware could also support virtual reality, due to its power, price point, and convenience.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] At the 2017 Game Developers Conference, Microsoft announced plans to support Windows Mixed Reality VR headsets on Xbox One in 2018, but the company later stated that it was initially focusing on PC platforms first, and that it wanted to focus on wireless VR solutions for consoles.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Games marketed by Microsoft as *Xbox One X Enhanced* have specific optimizations for graphical fidelity on the console's hardware.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Separate iconography denotes games that natively run at 4K resolution, or support HDR.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Existing games can be updated to provide these enhancements.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Though Xbox Games marketing head Aaron Greenberg stated that Xbox One X will have no exclusive titles, general manager of game publishing Shannon Loftis remarked in a follow-up interview that she was not sure on this point and that exclusivity would be "up to the game development community".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Xbox One X has been characterized as a competitor to the PlayStation 4 Pro, a hardware update of the PlayStation 4 released in late 2016 that similarly focuses on 4K gaming and improved virtual reality performance.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] In October 2016, Penello stated that the performance advantage of Xbox One X over the PS4 Pro would be "obvious", noting that the PS4 Pro's GPU only had 4.2 teraflops of graphical computing performance in comparison to Microsoft's stated 6 teraflops.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Some journalists thought that Microsoft's messaging and positioning of Scorpio alongside the release of Xbox One S were at odds with themselves and "confusing".
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Production of the Xbox One X was discontinued in July 2020 as Microsoft prepared for the transition to the then-upcoming Xbox Series X console.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Only the model launched in 2013 came bundled with Kinect.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Subsequent models did not include the Kinect, and Xbox One S and One X models dropped the Kinect-specific port.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Special launch edition with limited availability.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Subsequent price reductions are explained in the attached notes.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Retail price dropped to $349 in June 2015, $299 in May 2016 before Xbox One S launch, and finally $279 in June 2016 after Xbox One S launch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Price cut by $50 in June 2017 ahead of Xbox One X launch.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] 500 GB models cut to $249 and 1 TB models cut to $299.
[src:xbox-one/xbox-one-p02] Retail price dropped to $319 in May 2016 ahead of Xbox One S launch.
